observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the:
a. Local Development Council and the MPDC, together with the concerned implementing offices, in coordination with the Bids and Awards Committee (i) immediately look into the unimplemented projects under the 20% DF and determine the causes of their non- implementation; (ii) formulate/develop specific strategies/solutions to effectively implement development projects; (iii) consider formulating a timetable within which to complete the unimplemented projects; and (iv) review the costing of projects programmed twoto eight years ago to conform to the present conditions;
b. The Municipal Engineer (ME) (i) improve the planning and scheduling of work activities and manpower in order to facilitate completion of the Program of Work of unimplemented projects; and (ii) ensure that plans are accurate and projects estimates are based on standard and realistic amounts;
c. The MPDC (i) enhance monitoring of project implementation in coordination with the implementing offices; and (ii) submit regularly status reports of implementation to the Municipal Mayor for his information so that appropriate measures can be instituted to obtain optimal utilization of fund; and
d. Municipal Mayor (i) ensure the full or optimum utilization of the 20% DF in accordance with Section 5 of DILG and DBM JMC No. 2017-1 and ensure the effective and efficient implementation of the projects to maximize the developmental benefits of the intended beneficiaries; (ii) provide additional manpower in the Office of the MPDC and ME to assist them in implementing and monitoring development projects; and (iii) convene MPDC, ME and other offices department heads concerned to strongly pursue the completion of the projects to be implemented the soonest time possible in order to achieve the objectives of the said projects in providing socio-economic benefits to the intended beneficiaries and remind them of their duties and responsibilities.

We recommended that the:
a. GFPS Executive Committee:
i. continue in promoting and ensuring gender mainstreaming in local policy-making, planning, programming, budgeting, implementation, monitoring and evaluation;
ii. submit to the AT hard copy of the GAD Plan and Budget and GAD Accomplishment Report duly received by the DILG;
iii. set GAD Agenda to be addressed by the LGU during the three-year term of its leadership in accordance with the guidelines for preparation set forth by PCW Memorandum Circular No. 2018-04 dated September 19, 2018; and
iv. periodically (i) review, evaluate and recalibrate, as necessary, its GAD code to keep up with changes and development in addressing gender issues to ensure that the outcome of MGA’s GAD system remains in line with the government in achieving its GAD objectives; and (ii) prepare the corresponding Implementing Rules and Regulations (IRR) in accordance with PCW MC No. 2009-1 dated September 16, 2009 and Section 105 of MGA’s GAD Code;
b. MPDC, in coordination with the GFPS-TWG, complete the establishment of a GAD database containing the gender statistics and sex-disaggregated data of the Municipality in accordance with Section 37-D, Rule VI of the IRR of RA No. 9710 and henceforth keep it updated such that it may serve as a reliable basis for addressing gender issues and concern in GAD planning and budgeting for the ensuing years.

AAR CY 2020 Part II, Page 50-53 | We recommended that the:

Municipal Accountant (i) exert more efforts to finish updating the subsidiary ledgers for Construction in Progress as soon as possible and then, prepare the accounting entries to record the completed infrastructures in their respective accounts, along with the corresponding allowances for depreciation; 

(ii) in coordination with the Municipal Engineer, prepare a comprehensive report on the correct valuation of all infrastructure assets of the Municipality and record adjustments in the books of accounts as needed; 

(iii) henceforth, ensure that subsidiary ledgers for all infrastructure asset and construction in progress accounts are regularly updated;



Municipal Treasurer, as Property and Supply Officer in the absence of a GSO, (i) prepare a detailed property record for the municipal infrastructure assets based on the report of the Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Engineer; and 

(ii) ensure that henceforth, such property record is regularly updated and reconciled with the accounting records; and



Municipal Mayor (i) consider the creation of a plantilla position for GSO, subject to availability of funds; and 



(ii) enjoin all department heads to strictly comply with the accounting and reporting guidelines for the Local Roads Asset Management System as provided under COA Circular No. 2015-008.

AAR CY 2020 Part II, Page 63-71 | We recommended that the:

Human Resource Management Officer submit (i) a copy of duly accomplished monthly time records and approved DTRs of municipal employees and personnel who received Covid-19 Hazard Pay in CY 2020; and



(ii) office orders authorizing the municipal employees and personnel to physically report for work in their respective offices or work stations on the prescribed hours during the implementation of ECQ;

Municipal Budget Officer submit a valid justification for signing the obligation requests for Covid-19 Hazard Pay totaling ₱953,561.57 despite having invalid fund sources;

Municipal Mayor submit a reasonable explanation for allowing payment of Covid-19 Hazard Pay to barangay officials and workers and the DOH personnel (i) by way of direct payment to individuals instead of making a fund transfer to the government agencies concerned, covered by a written trust agreement; and (ii) using BGCM and realigned portion of DRRMF as fund source in the payment thereof; and

Municipal Accountant ensure that all claims for hazard pay or other personnel benefits are in accordance with pertinent accounting and budgeting rules and regulation and duly supported with complete and proper documentation.

We recommended that the:

Municipal Mayor (i) communicate to the DILG through the MLGOO the importance of entering into a MOA for every fund transfer as required under COA Circular No. 94-013 dated December 13, 1994; and (ii) submit a reasonable explanation for issuing NTP prior to the approval of contract;

Municipal Engineer submit (i) a summary report of all inspections conducted on the project, duly supported with duly certified inspection reports, statements of time elapsed and pictures of work items; (ii) detailed engineering design for the project with complete plans and drawings; (iii) duly approved program of works and detailed computation of the approved budget for the contract; (iv) project implementation schedule and approved PERT/CPM Network Diagram, and (v) a satisfactory explanation for the delay in the completion of the project, duly supported with valid documentation;

BAC Chairperson submit a copy of all available documentation on the procurement activities conducted for the project, including the APP, bidding documents, minutes of BAC meetings and negotiations, results of mandatory reviews, bidders’ final quotations, performance security and other related documents; and

Municipal Accountant submit all the lacking supporting documents and henceforth, ensure that all disbursements are supported with complete documentation pursuant to Section 4.6 of P.D. No. 1445.

We recommended that the:
Municipal Inventory Committee conduct a complete physical count of PPE, including the roads and other road network components, in accordance with Section 124 of the NGAS Manual for LGUs, Volume I, and prepare the Report on Physical Count of the Road Network System using the format provided under Annex “C” of COA Circular No. 2015-008;
Municipal Engineer prepare the Report on Local Road Network using the format provided under Annex “A” of COA Circular No. 2015-008 and submit the same to the Municipal Accountant and Municipal Treasurer, copy furnished the Audit Team;
Municipal Treasurer, as the Property Officer, prepare and maintain the Road Network Property Cards for all roads and its components, using the format provided under Annex “E” of COA Circular No. 2015-008;
Municipal Accountant (i) upon submission of the Report on Local Road Network and the Report on Physical Count of the Road Network System submitted by the Municipal Engineer and the Inventory Committee, reconcile the said reports with accounting records in order to determine the correct amount of the road networks to be recorded; (ii) prepare the lapsing schedule of depreciation of road networks for CY 2019, with supporting computation for unrecorded depreciation in prior years, in order to determine the correct amount of accumulated depreciation as of December 31, 2019; (iii) prepare the journal entries to record the correct amount of road networks and accumulated depreciation in the books of accounts; (iv) prepare the subsidiary accounting records for roads and road components in accordance with Section VII.a.3 of COA Circular No. 2015-008; and (v) henceforth, ensure adequate disclosure of information regarding the Local Road Network on the Notes to the Financial Statements as prescribed under Annex “B” of COA Circular No. 2015-008; and
Municipal Mayor (i) cause the creation of a plantilla position for the General Services Officer; (ii) through the Human Resource Management Officer, initiate the search for qualified applicants for the said position; and (iii) enjoin the concerned department heads to comply with all the requirements of COA Circular No. 2015-008.

We recommended that the Municipal Accountant:

submit (i) a revised SUCA as of December 31, 2018 covering all Advances accounts in all funds including SEF and TF, with complete and detailed information on the date granted, due date for liquidation and status of accountable officer; and (ii) a copy of general and subsidiary ledgers for Advances accounts under SEF and TF;

impose strictly the provision requiring all accountable officers to fully and promptly liquidate their cash advances as soon as the purpose for which it was given has been served or at the end of each year, whichever comes first;

cause the issuance of demand letters to all accountable officers who have unliquidated cash advances as of December 31, 2018 and still failed to liquidate the same as of September 30, 2019; and

henceforth, ensure prompt submission of reports and records pertaining to cash advances to allow timely review of the same.

We recommended that the Municipal Treasurer:

inform the Provincial Treasurer that the provision for granting discount on RPT as provided under the New Revenue Code of Palawan is in conflict with Section 246 of RA No. 7160, Article 342 of the IRR of RA No. 7160 and Section 177 of the LTOM;

propose to the Provincial Treasurer the issuance of a revised Notice of Payment for CY 2018 or any other means to disseminate information to taxpayers, clarifying that RPT payments made during the first quarter of the year are not considered “advanced” but instead “prompt” and subject only to 10% discount;

collect the amount of under-collection of RPT due from taxpayers for CY 2018 but only after providing them clear and sufficient information on the correct discounts and taxes due, notwithstanding the issuance of a Notice of Delinquency in accordance with Section 254 of RA No. 7160 and Article 345 of its IRR; and

henceforth, adhere to Article 342 of the IRR of RA No. 7160 in granting discounts on RPT payments.
